N1  - E16. Teachable Agents And Learning-by-Teaching. 
N1  - E17. Teachable agents (TAs) are virtual agents that simulate a less knowledgeable peer to promote students' actions of learning-by-teaching (Zhao et al, 2012).. 
N1  - E18. TAs are reported to have an impact on enhancing students' domain knowledge (Fantuzzo et al, 1992), self-efficacy (Pareto et al, 2011), learning engagement, and motivation (Chase et al, 2009).. 
N1  - E19. The history of TAs has been developing with the application of intelligent systems in education, such as DENISE (Development of Environment for an Intelligent Student in Economics) (Nicolas, 1993).. 
N1  - E20. Generative AI And Teachable Agents. 
N1  - E21. GenAI technology provides highly natural, human-like conversations that are contextual, personalized, and nuanced (Chan &amp; Hu, 2023; Matthew et al, 2023; Sun et al, 2024a).. 
N1  - E22. GenAI-powered TAs could generate more dynamic responses, offer personalized feedback, and adapt to individual learning styles (Johnson &amp; Lester, 2018).. 
N1  - E23. Integrating large language models (LLMs) allows TAs to understand and respond to student input effectively and naturally (Jin et al, 2024).. 
N1  - E24. Students' Perceptions And Challenges. 
N1  - E25. Students' trust in GenAI tools influences their adoption of these tools and their performance in computer science courses (Amoozadeh et al, 2023).. 
N1  - E26. The design of GenAI applications did not consider students' perceptions, which could be attributed to the limiting nature of GenAI in education (Avgerinou et al, 2023; Xue et al, 2024).. 
N1  - E27. It is crucial to explore students' perceptions of GenAI in an authentic classroom setting to guide the future design directions of GenAI applications in education and AI-assisted instructions.. 
N1  - E28. Technical Challenges. 
N1  - E29. Implementing GenAI-powered TAs in classrooms faces technical challenges, such as creating TAs that can learn from and adapt to student needs, abilities, and interests (Crompton et al, 2022).. 
N1  - E30. TAs may not fully comprehend students' open-ended responses, limiting communication and meaningful learning (Matsuda et al, 2020).. 
N1  - E31. Pedagogical Approaches. 
N1  - E32. Developing relevant pedagogical models and instructional strategies to support TA-assisted instruction is crucial (Chan &amp; Tsi, 2023).. 
N1  - E33. Fostering relationships between students and TAs is essential for enhancing students' sense of ownership and agency in learning (Silvervarg et al, 2021; Kim &amp; Cho, 2023).. 
N1  - E34. Systematic instructional design is necessary to support meaningful learning (Kim, 2024).. 
N1  - E35. Student Perceptions. 
N1  - E36. Students' perceptions on GenAI-powered TAs are highly valued, as they can direct future development and utilization of TAs in classrooms.. 
N1  - E37. The study collected qualitative data from students through observations, semi-structured focus-group interviews, and open-ended survey questions to understand their experiences and perceptions of the GenAI-powered TA.. 
N1  - E38. Roles Of TAs. 
N1  - E39. Students perceived TAs as learning companions, infusing subjective characteristics, and occupying the role of tutor, helping the TA to improve math performance by providing advice, support, and knowledge.. 
N1  - E40. Students approached the TA as a peer they could socialize with, making their learning more exciting and enriching.. 
N1  - E41. Students perceived the TA as a peer with different abilities, acknowledging the differences between AI and human intelligence and how AI learns differently from humans.. 
N1  - E42. Opportunities Of Learning With a TA. 
N1  - E43. Students saw the TA as a learning facilitator, helping them grasp learning content and streamline learning processes.. 
N1  - E44. Students involved the TA in the sequence of steps to solve the math problem together, as demonstrated by the creative problem-solving process (CPS) model.. 
N1  - E45. Students appreciated that the TA promotes diverse pedagogical approaches, such as problem-based learning, scenario-based learning, gamification, and mission-based learning.. 
N1  - E46. Students perceived that learning with a GenAI-powered TA fosters their autonomy, taking more active roles in their learning and exhibiting a sense of responsibility.. 
N1  - E47. Challenges Of Learning With a TA. 
N1  - E48. Students faced difficulties in explaining complex concepts to the AI, feeling sorry for the AI because they didn't know how to alternate questions to help it think from different sides and respond to AI's mistakes.. 
N1  - E49. Students experienced technical issues, such as slow responses, glitches, and difficulties in understanding the AI's language and slang.. 
N1  - E50. Students wished for more practice and feedback, as well as the ability to take notes freely and reach out to other platforms to bring more materials and activities to show AI.. 
N1  - E51. Learning Outcomes. 
N1  - E52. Students' emotional capacity, such as growth mindset and resilience, improved by interacting with the TA (Zou et al, 2023).. 
N1  - E53. Improving subject-matter knowledge was found to be another opportunity to learn with the TA, as students expressed that their mathematical knowledge improved on the topic of rate and ratio (Fantuzzo et al, 1992; Kober, 2015).. 
N1  - E54. Students highlighted that their application of knowledge improved, as teaching the TA creates an opportunity for students to apply their knowledge in different contexts (Bandi et al, 2023).. 
N1  - E55. Affective Domain. 
N1  - E56. Students expressed a high level of enthusiasm for the learning experience, and their self-efficacy improved as they taught and helped the TA learn (Bargh &amp; Schul, 1980).. 
N1  - E57. Interacting with the TA enhanced students' intrinsic motivation, as learning-by-teaching and teaching others can be an intrinsically motivating experience (Chase et al, 2009; Biswas et al, 2016).. 
N1  - E58. Interdisciplinary Learning And AI Literacy. 
N1  - E59. Students expressed that learning with a TA creates an opportunity to synthesize knowledge, concepts, and practices from different academic disciplines (e.g., computer science and math) (P15).. 
N1  - E60. Interacting with the AI agent builds a positive attitude toward AI, and students illustrated that they are aware of both weaknesses and strengths of AI (Kim et al, 2024).. 
