N1  - E16. Ai Literacy. 
N1  - E17. Artificial intelligence (AI) is increasingly present in many aspects of human life, making AI literacy, comprising knowledge and skills for critical interaction with AI, essential (Russell &amp; Norvig, 2015; Long &amp; Magerko, 2020).. 
N1  - E18. AI literacy encompasses a broad range of resources for teachers and learners, including curricula, digital tools, and teaching guides (Ng et al, 2021).. 
N1  - E19. Multilingual Learners And AI Literacy. 
N1  - E20. Multilingual learners must acquire AI literacy, necessitating tailored pedagogical practices that integrate linguistic resources from various languages throughout the curriculum (Vogel et al, 2019).. 
N1  - E21. There is a mutually beneficial relationship between acquiring second language proficiency and AI literacy, as AI-based technologies can facilitate interactive dialogues in multiple languages and provide tools for learners to explore and express their bilingual and multilingual identities (Topsakal and Topsakal, 2022; Du &amp; Tate, 2024).. 
N1  - E22. AI literacy activities that capitalize on learners' existing linguistic skills offer significant benefits to multilingual learners, and conversational agents are particularly suitable for linguistic practices due to their design, which enables interaction through reading, writing, speaking, and listening (García et al, 2017).. 
N1  - E23. Pedagogical Strategies. 
N1  - E24. Three pedagogical strategies for multilingual elementary and middle school students aimed at enhancing specific AI literacy competencies using conversational agent technologies are: (1) storytelling to model AI decision-making, (2) role-playing as an AI to demonstrate programmability and learning from data, and (3) programming text-to-speech-to-text AI to illustrate sensor functionality and action-reaction concepts.. 
